the next round.

00:09:44,857 --> 00:09:47,060
Or do you want to hear
what Mark has to say?

00:09:47,060 --> 00:09:49,629
Mark's quiet over there.
Yeah, Mark's always quiet.

00:09:49,629 --> 00:09:51,431
I always want to entertain

00:09:51,431 --> 00:09:52,999
what's in front of me,
too, so...
Yeah.

00:09:52,999 --> 00:09:55,401
Want to throw your foot in,
please do.

00:09:55,401 --> 00:09:58,905
So, I'll match their offer,
but at 3% interest.

00:09:58,905 --> 00:10:01,908
But I'm gonna suggest that
we don't push for the series A.

00:10:01,908 --> 00:10:03,176
That's a mistake.

00:10:03,176 --> 00:10:05,745
You will never be a Plated
if you stay small.

00:10:06,946 --> 00:10:08,481
[ Sighs ]

00:10:08,481 --> 00:10:11,217
Look, you're already positioned
to scale, right?
Yes.

00:10:11,217 --> 00:10:13,252
This is tough.

00:10:13,252 --> 00:10:14,687
You know what?

00:10:14,687 --> 00:10:16,656
I would not be
a billionaire

00:10:16,656 --> 00:10:18,291
if I had just kept on
raising money

00:10:18,291 --> 00:10:20,493
over and over
and over again.

00:10:20,493 --> 00:10:21,628
I'm with it.
Right?

00:10:21,628 --> 00:10:23,396
Yeah.
Damn, that's nice to say.

00:10:23,396 --> 00:10:24,931
Greiner: We're not gonna
have to keep raising.
Herjavec: God.

00:10:24,931 --> 00:10:26,666
We're gonna be doing
so well...
It's true.

00:10:26,666 --> 00:10:28,468
That's just putting it
on the table right there.
...we won't have to
keep raising.

00:10:28,468 --> 00:10:30,603
"Here you go, homey."
Jared, here's how I look at it.

00:10:30,603 --> 00:10:32,438
You know, you have three very
different people sitting here.

00:10:32,438 --> 00:10:34,607
I do.
I don't think
we're going to have to worry.

00:10:34,607 --> 00:10:36,175
Kevin wants to, like,
raise more money.

00:10:36,175 --> 00:10:37,610
But what I like to do

00:10:37,610 --> 00:10:41,681
is I like to get so many sales
and do it so fast

00:10:41,681 --> 00:10:43,116
and blitz out so fast...
Exactly.

00:10:43,116 --> 00:10:45,151
So, Lori, you and I
should be working together.

00:10:45,151 --> 00:10:48,021
...that you're not going to have
to do a whole bunch of raising.

00:10:48,021 --> 00:10:49,322
She's right.
She's actually right on that.
Right?

00:10:49,322 --> 00:10:52,525
Yeah. You know what, Jared?
I'll change my offer.

00:10:52,525 --> 00:10:54,060
I'm not gonna do it
as a loan.

00:10:54,060 --> 00:10:55,628
I'm gonna do it as equity.

00:10:55,628 --> 00:10:59,465
I'll offer you $500,000
for 7%.

00:10:59,465 --> 00:11:01,434
Did you want me in on it?

00:11:01,434 --> 00:11:03,903
Did you make an offer to me
earlier?
I'll do that deal as equity
right now.

00:11:03,903 --> 00:11:05,238
Done.
Both of you?

00:11:05,238 --> 00:11:06,673
Us?
Oh, the two of us,
you mean?

00:11:06,673 --> 00:11:09,575
Would you be willing to go in
with Mark as an equity deal,

00:11:09,575 --> 00:11:12,979
$500,000, 8%, 4% and 4%,
call it a deal?

00:11:12,979 --> 00:11:15,548
You make it 10%,
I'll split it with her.

00:11:15,548 --> 00:11:17,717
If you make it 10%,
I'll do that deal.

00:11:17,717 --> 00:11:20,019
As equity.
Can we go up a little bit
in dollars?

00:11:21,421 --> 00:11:22,955
You're getting two Sharks.
Come on.

00:11:22,955 --> 00:11:24,657
Greiner and Cuban:
You're getting two Sharks.
I know.

00:11:24,657 --> 00:11:26,192
And we're gonna
increase your sales.
Greiner: Come on, baby.

00:11:26,192 --> 00:11:27,927
And think about it ‐‐
Okay, 10%, deal.

00:11:27,927 --> 00:11:28,728
Done.
Done.

00:11:28,728 --> 00:11:29,562
Done.
Boom!

00:11:29,562 --> 00:11:31,197
Let's shake that salad.

00:11:31,197 --> 00:11:33,032
‐Let's shake the salad.
‐Congratulations.

00:11:33,032 --> 00:11:35,001
Thanks, guys.
I appreciate everyone's time.

00:11:35,001 --> 00:11:36,335
Thank you very much.
Good job, Jared, man.

00:11:36,335 --> 00:11:37,336
Thanks, guys.
Great job.

00:11:37,336 --> 00:11:39,772
Herjavec: Good job.
Congrats.

00:11:39,772 --> 00:11:41,107
Yeah, having two Sharks
on board,

00:11:41,107 --> 00:11:42,341
we're ready
to shake this thing up,

00:11:42,341 --> 00:11:43,976
get out there, sell some jars,

00:11:43,976 --> 00:11:45,945
change the world
one jar at a time.

00:11:45,945 --> 00:11:48,748
I want to say, "I wouldn't
be a billionaire..."

00:11:48,748 --> 00:11:50,049
[ Laughs ]

00:11:50,049 --> 00:11:52,251
I mean, that's just,
like, there.

00:11:52,251 --> 00:11:53,853
You know what?
And I like saying it.

00:11:53,853 --> 00:11:54,987
[ Laughs ]

00:11:57,523 --> 00:11:58,725
Narrator: In Season 10,

00:11:58,725 --> 00:12:00,893
Noel Durity made a deal
with Mark Cuban

00:12:00,893 --> 00:12:04,263
for his patented hairstyling
tool, the Twist It Up Comb.

00:12:04,263 --> 00:12:05,765
Is that a yes?
It's a yes.

00:12:05,765 --> 00:12:07,867
Narrator: Let's see
what he's up to now.

00:12:07,867 --> 00:12:10,436
I invented the Twist It Up Comb
because I wanted to provide

00:12:10,436 --> 00:12:12,305
a styling comb
for the Black community

00:12:12,305 --> 00:12:14,640
that allowed us
to embrace our natural twists.

00:12:14,640 --> 00:12:17,877
Twist It Up Comb is now sold
on my website, on Amazon,

00:12:17,877 --> 00:12:21,881
and now over 250
beauty‐supply stores nationwide.

00:12:21,881 --> 00:12:23,850
Less than two years
after "Shark Tank,"

00:12:23,850 --> 00:12:26,619
we have done over $2 million
in sales.

00:12:26,619 --> 00:12:28,387
But just three months
after airing,

00:12:28,387 --> 00:12:30,323
I saw that my comb
was being knocked off

00:12:30,323 --> 00:12:33,326
and being sold to beauty‐supply
stores around the country.

00:12:33,326 --> 00:12:35,194
Calm before the storm.

00:12:35,194 --> 00:12:39,365
To see all my hard work
be copycatted broke my heart.

00:12:39,365 --> 00:12:41,768
I consulted a lawyer
and took off on a road trip

00:12:41,768 --> 00:12:43,236
to over 100 stores,

00:12:43,236 --> 00:12:46,472
over 24 cities
from New York to California.

00:12:46,472 --> 00:12:48,741
We ended up confiscating
over 1,000 combs,

00:12:48,741 --> 00:12:51,444
over 40 invoices
I used as evidence

00:12:51,444 --> 00:12:54,447
to win a six‐figure settlement
against these copycats.

00:12:54,447 --> 00:12:56,816
You just got in the car
and got it done,

00:12:56,816 --> 00:12:58,451
but that's what you do,
my guy.

00:12:58,451 --> 00:13:01,754
Knock‐offs are a pestilence
on every successful product,

00:13:01,754 --> 00:13:03,823
and Noel did not back down.

00:13:03,823 --> 00:13:06,926
We took every measure possible
to deal with them,

00:13:06,926 --> 00:13:09,428
and there are gonna be more,
and we'll keep on fighting.

00:13:09,428 --> 00:13:11,063
How big are we gonna
get this thing, Noel?

00:13:11,063 --> 00:13:13,866
Big as God wants me to make it,
as big as I can grind.

00:13:13,866 --> 00:13:16,035
Noel's future with
Twist It Up is incredible.

00:13:16,035 --> 00:13:19,405
He is the dominant product
in this space.

00:13:19,405 --> 00:13:21,707
So as we build visibility
and awareness,

00:13:21,707 --> 00:13:23,776
this product
is just gonna skyrocket.

00:13:25,578 --> 00:13:27,213
Durity:
As a Black‐owned business,

00:13:27,213 --> 00:13:29,448
it's very important
for me to succeed

00:13:29,448 --> 00:13:32,885
because I represent the idea
that it is possible

00:13:32,885 --> 00:13:36,155
someone that looks like me
can succeed in America.

00:13:36,155 --> 00:13:38,925
It gives the culture hope.

00:13:38,925 --> 00:13:42,795
When you look at me,
I want it to inspire you.

00:13:42,795 --> 00:13:45,131
And I think going through
this entire process

00:13:45,131 --> 00:13:48,267
with "Shark Tank," reaching
the success that I have reached,

00:13:48,267 --> 00:13:50,903
I honestly think that is exactly
what is happening.

00:13:50,903 --> 00:13:53,206
It is allowing me
to fulfill my purpose

00:13:53,206 --> 00:13:55,374
and share this idea
with the world

00:13:55,374 --> 00:13:56,976
and that they can find
the courage

00:13:56,976 --> 00:13:59,445
to go after their dream
looking at my life.

00:13:59,445 --> 00:14:00,613
And I want to thank "Shark Tank"

00:14:00,613 --> 00:14:02,782
and I want to thank Mark Cuban
for all of that.

00:14:02,782 --> 00:14:08,621
♪♪

00:14:17,029 --> 00:14:20,166
Narrator: Next up is a product
designed to relieve stress.

00:14:20,166 --> 00:14:25,438
♪♪

00:14:25,438 --> 00:14:30,710
♪♪

00:14:30,710 --> 00:14:32,011
Hello, Sharks.

00:14:32,011 --> 00:14:34,413
I'm Nancy Rothner
from Lewes, Delaware,

00:14:34,413 --> 00:14:35,882
and I'm here
to talk about something

00:14:35,882 --> 00:14:38,684
we have all experienced ‐‐
stress.

00:14:38,684 --> 00:14:40,319
And as a matter of fact,

00:14:40,319 --> 00:14:44,156
I'm feeling some of it now
standing in front of all of you.

00:14:44,156 --> 00:14:46,058
Now, I think you'll all agree,

00:14:46,058 --> 00:14:48,261
with the current
pandemic situation,

00:14:48,261 --> 00:14:51,564
stress has reached
an all‐time high,

00:14:51,564 --> 00:14:53,966
and this may seem unbelievable,

00:14:53,966 --> 00:14:56,936
but I believe I've come up
with a solution to stress.

00:14:56,936 --> 00:15:00,172
And it's so simple,
you'll be saying, "Pinch me."

00:15:00,172 --> 00:15:03,242
And that's what it's called ‐‐
Pinch Me Therapy Dough.

00:15:03,242 --> 00:15:06,412
It's an innovative,
aromatherapy‐infused,

00:15:06,412 --> 00:15:09,849
moldable, multisensory
stress reliever.

00:15:09,849 --> 00:15:11,417
At the first hint of stress,

00:15:11,417 --> 00:15:14,120
simply take some out, knead it,

00:15:14,120 --> 00:15:16,188
and allow the calming to begin.

00:15:16,188 --> 00:15:18,524
Now, for the last 20 years,
I've worked as a therapist

00:15:18,524 --> 00:15:20,326
in the field
of stress reduction.

00:15:20,326 --> 00:15:22,261
I've seen time and time again

00:15:22,261 --> 00:15:24,664
what's most effective
to quickly de‐stress.

00:15:24,664 --> 00:15:27,800
And I wanted to find a way
to reach more people.

00:15:27,800 --> 00:15:30,870
I'm confident with your help
and expertise,

00:15:30,870 --> 00:15:33,940
we can reduce stress
around the world.

00:15:33,940 --> 00:15:38,744
I'm seeking $300,000 in exchange
for 7% of my company.

00:15:38,744 --> 00:15:39,912
‐Oh!
‐Wow.

00:15:39,912 --> 00:15:42,648
I just got stressed.
Yeah. Now we're stressed.

00:15:42,648 --> 00:15:45,618
There are some samples in front
of you that should help.

00:15:45,618 --> 00:15:49,388
So, Sharks, who wants to
pinch me and make some dough?

00:15:51,490 --> 00:15:54,327
So we just scoop it out?
Scoop it out, yeah.

00:15:54,327 --> 00:15:56,128
And there's no wrong way
to use it.

00:15:56,128 --> 00:15:57,296
You can knead it, massage it,

00:15:57,296 --> 00:15:59,465
take as little or as much
as you like out,

00:15:59,465 --> 00:16:01,467
and you can use it
over and over again.

00:16:01,467 --> 00:16:02,635
Oh, it feels great.
This one smells fantastic.

00:16:02,635 --> 00:16:04,537
Thank you.
I love the yellow.
Yeah.

00:16:04,537 --> 00:16:07,073
The scent component's there
because when we're stressed,

00:16:07,073 --> 00:16:09,442
what happens is everything
in our system runs tight,

00:16:09,442 --> 00:16:11,277
including our breath.
Grr!

00:16:11,277 --> 00:16:14,347
Since our brain is so heavily
hardwired to our fingers,

00:16:14,347 --> 00:16:17,083
this helps us to become
a little bit more centered.

00:16:17,083 --> 00:16:19,652
Then the tension that we have
in our body

00:16:19,652 --> 00:16:21,020
has a way to release out
through the fingers.

00:16:21,020 --> 00:16:23,723
So if my child gets ahold
of this, no problem?

00:16:23,723 --> 00:16:26,225
Yes. Lab‐tested safe
and nontoxic.

00:16:26,225 --> 00:16:27,793
It tastes hideous.

00:16:27,793 --> 00:16:31,330
So I don't think anybody
would even consider it, yeah.
Right, okay.

00:16:31,330 --> 00:16:33,866
Greiner: Is this lavender,
the purple?

00:16:33,866 --> 00:16:35,668
Yes.
That's lavender?

00:16:35,668 --> 00:16:36,769
John:
Oh, it tastes like soap.

00:16:36,769 --> 00:16:38,270
Oh, it's terrible.
Cuban: Tried it, yeah.

00:16:38,270 --> 00:16:40,172
Give it to Daymond.
He'll eat anything.

00:16:40,172 --> 00:16:41,941
She says to you,
"It tastes terrible."

00:16:41,941 --> 00:16:43,442
Yeah, I told you
it tastes terrible.

00:16:43,442 --> 00:16:44,877
John: Oh, my God.
[ Laughs ]

00:16:46,412 --> 00:16:48,948
Tell us about you,
about your background.

00:16:48,948 --> 00:16:50,182
What's your story?

00:16:50,182 --> 00:16:52,551
I worked as a stockbroker,
did that for five years.

00:16:52,551 --> 00:16:55,087
You were a stockbroker?
I was, yeah.

00:16:55,087 --> 00:16:59,025
But then I volunteered at
a shelter for domestic violence,

00:16:59,025 --> 00:17:00,159
and that just inspired me.

00:17:00,159 --> 00:17:02,161
I knew that's what
I wanted to do.

00:17:02,161 --> 00:17:04,030
So I studied, trained.
I worked so hard.

00:17:04,030 --> 00:17:06,499
And I became certified
in therapeutic services

00:17:06,499 --> 00:17:10,236
so I would be able to help
people overcome addictions,

00:17:10,236 --> 00:17:12,671
phobia, stress ‐‐ you name it.

00:17:12,671 --> 00:17:16,776
So one night, I thought,
"How can I help more people?"

00:17:16,776 --> 00:17:20,546
And then [Snaps fingers] boom,
I had that light‐bulb moment.

00:17:20,546 --> 00:17:24,650
I knew exactly what to do.
I got to work, never stopped.

00:17:24,650 --> 00:17:25,985
And the result is Pinch Me.

00:17:25,985 --> 00:17:28,888
So what does it cost for you
to make, and what is the retail?

00:17:28,888 --> 00:17:31,323
Sure. All‐in cost
for the smallest, $4.50,

00:17:31,323 --> 00:17:33,225
with retail $14.99.

00:17:33,225 --> 00:17:36,962
For the large, $7.50,
retail $24.99.

00:17:36,962 --> 00:17:38,030
What are your sales?

00:17:38,030 --> 00:17:40,566
Lifetime sales are $5.3 million.

00:17:40,566 --> 00:17:41,734
‐What?
‐Wow.
‐What?

00:17:41,734 --> 00:17:42,735
‐Yes. Yes.
‐Really?

00:17:42,735 --> 00:17:44,270
Yeah, how long
is that lifetime?

00:17:44,270 --> 00:17:46,205
Well, actually, 2015,

00:17:46,205 --> 00:17:49,108
I walked into a few stores
to introduce myself.

00:17:49,108 --> 00:17:52,645
They immediately said yes,
sold out, were placing orders.

00:17:52,645 --> 00:17:57,216
And then the summer of 2015, my
husband and I were blindsided.

00:17:57,216 --> 00:17:59,618
He was diagnosed with leukemia.

00:17:59,618 --> 00:18:00,619
Oh, no.

00:18:00,619 --> 00:18:02,088
And so suddenly our life

00:18:02,088 --> 00:18:04,757
was all about
just getting through the day.

00:18:04,757 --> 00:18:08,027
So I really had to
put sales on hold.

00:18:08,027 --> 00:18:09,261
He came through it great.

00:18:09,261 --> 00:18:10,329
He's doing wonderfully.
Great.

00:18:10,329 --> 00:18:11,097
Great to hear.

00:18:11,097 --> 00:18:13,399
And now 2016,

00:18:13,399 --> 00:18:15,701
I had sales of $200,000.

00:18:15,701 --> 00:18:19,905
Then the next year, 2017,
I did $800,000.

00:18:19,905 --> 00:18:22,708
Wow.
Then the next year, in 2018,

00:18:22,708 --> 00:18:24,677
we did $1.6 million.

00:18:24,677 --> 00:18:27,313
Then last year, $1.95 million.

00:18:27,313 --> 00:18:30,282
And the beginning of this year,
I was on track to go higher,

00:18:30,282 --> 00:18:31,784
at least $2.5 million.

00:18:31,784 --> 00:18:34,153
Had all these purchase orders,
then COVID hit.

00:18:34,153 --> 00:18:35,888
And so what's happened
since COVID?

00:18:35,888 --> 00:18:37,423
How has that
affected you?

00:18:37,423 --> 00:18:39,658
Yeah, I mean, obviously,
it's had a big impact

00:18:39,658 --> 00:18:41,293
when all the stores are closed.

00:18:41,293 --> 00:18:45,164
At this point, our sales to date
are $760,000,

00:18:45,164 --> 00:18:48,334
and I expect this year
we'll be at $1.2 million.

00:18:48,334 --> 00:18:50,269
What would the business
make all‐in?

00:18:50,269 --> 00:18:52,171
This year,
it's not our best year.

00:18:52,171 --> 00:18:54,140
We'll probably make $220,000.

00:18:54,140 --> 00:18:55,975
Last year, though ‐‐
After you pay yourself.

00:18:55,975 --> 00:18:57,376
Yes, after I pay myself.

00:18:57,376 --> 00:18:59,178
That's fantastic.
Thank you.

00:18:59,178 --> 00:19:02,414
Last year, after I paid myself,
we profited $584,000.

00:19:02,414 --> 00:19:03,682
‐Yeah!
‐Wow!
‐Wow!

00:19:03,682 --> 00:19:06,385
Thank you.
That'll reduce your stress
right there.

00:19:06,385 --> 00:19:07,453
You know what, Nancy?

00:19:07,453 --> 00:19:09,121
Congratulations
on what you've done.

00:19:09,121 --> 00:19:11,690
It's just not a space
that I really want to be in.

00:19:11,690 --> 00:19:13,359
So for those reasons,
I'm out.

00:19:13,359 --> 00:19:14,960
Okay.

00:19:14,960 --> 00:19:17,029
I'm thinking about it.
I like it as a customer.

00:19:17,029 --> 00:19:18,764
But just not for me.

00:19:18,764 --> 00:19:21,500
I wouldn't see any passion
in trying to get it out there

00:19:21,500 --> 00:19:22,535
or helping,

00:19:22,535 --> 00:19:24,837
so I'm out.

00:19:24,837 --> 00:19:26,305
Thank you.

00:19:26,305 --> 00:19:29,141
The problem is, you never built
your digital direct to customer

00:19:29,141 --> 00:19:31,844
while you were experiencing
this growth in retail.

00:19:31,844 --> 00:19:33,012
Exactly.

00:19:33,012 --> 00:19:35,548
I'm interested,
but my offer's gonna be sharky

00:19:35,548 --> 00:19:37,816
in the sense that I don't know
what I don't know

00:19:37,816 --> 00:19:39,818
about the digital pivot, okay?
Okay, alright.

00:19:39,818 --> 00:19:41,921
And that's where I'm interested
in blowing it up,

00:19:41,921 --> 00:19:46,058
because I feel at risk in retail
for all kinds of products.

00:19:46,058 --> 00:19:48,794
I'll give you the $300,000
for 25%.

00:19:48,794 --> 00:19:50,396
‐Ooh!
‐Mnh!
‐Okay.

00:19:50,396 --> 00:19:53,098
Thank you. I appreciate that.
Hey, it's what
I'm comfortable with.

00:19:53,098 --> 00:19:55,034
